<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_order_mod_n" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Order of modular units</title>
    <objectives>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Define the order of elements of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Define the notion of a primitive root modulo <m>n</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Begin exploring the existence of primitive roots.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </objectives>
<subsection xml:id="ss_order_prim_roots">
    <title>Order and primitive roots</title>
    <p>
        Recall Euler's theorem: if <m>n</m> is a positive integer and <m>a\in \Z</m> is relatively prime to <m>n</m>, then <m>a^{\phi(n)}\equiv 1 \pmod n</m>. Equivalently, in the language of modular rings, given <m>r=[a]_n\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>r^{\phi(n)}=[a]_n^{\phi(n)}=[a^{\phi(n)}]=1</mrow>
        </md>.
        As an illustration of the economy of the modular ring language, let's re-prove this result.
    </p>
    <proof>
        <title>Modular ring proof of Euler's theorem</title>
        <p>
         Let <m>n</m> be a positive element, and let <m>r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}</m> be the distinct elements of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, so that 
         <md>
            <mrow>(\Z/n\Z)^* \amp = \{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\}</mrow>
         </md>. 
         (Note: although we have <m>r_i=[a_i]_n</m> for some integer <m>a_i</m>, we will not need to make use of these integers in our argument; we will only use properties of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> discussed in the previous section.) 
        </p>
        <p>
            Now, given any element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, we claim that we have the set equality 
            <md>
                <mrow>\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\} \amp = \{r\,r_1, r\, r_{2},\dots, r\, r_{\phi(n)}\}</mrow>
            </md>.
            Indeed, from <xref ref="th_units_mod_n"/>, we know that <m>r\, r_i\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, since <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is closed under multiplication. Thus 
            <md>
                <mrow>\{r\,r_1, r\,r_2,\dots, r\,r_{\phi(n)}\} \amp\subseteq (\Z/n\Z)^*=\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\} </mrow>
            </md>.
            For the other inclusion, we use the fact that there is an element <m>r^{-1}\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> satisfying <m>r\,r^{-1}=1</m>. Given any element <m>r_i\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, letting <m>r_j=r^{-1}\cdot r_i</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>r\,r_j \amp = r(r^{-1}r_i)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = (rr^{-1})r_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 1r_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = r_i</mrow>
            </md>.
            Having shown <m>\{r_1,r_2,\dots, r_{\phi(n)}\}=\{rr_1,rr_2,\dots, rr_{\phi(n)}\}</m>, we see that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i \amp =\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}rr_i</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = r^{\phi(n)}\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i</mrow>
            </md>.
            Letting <m>s=\prod_{i=1}^{\phi(n)}r_i</m>, the above equality becomes 
            <md>
                <mrow>s \amp =r^{\phi(n)}s</mrow>
            </md>.
            Since <m>s\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, it can be cancelled multiplicatively by multiplying both sides by <m>s^{-1}</m>. We conclude that <m>1=r^{\phi(n)}</m>, as desired. 
        </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
        From Euler's theorem we know that for all <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> there is at least one positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>r^k=1</m>: namely, <m>k=\phi(n)</m>. It follows from the well-ordering property of the integers that there is thus a smallest positive integer <m>k</m> satisfying <m>r^k=1</m>. We call this the <em>order</em> of <m>r</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_order_modular_unit">
    <title>Order of a modular unit</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\ord r</m></usage>
      <description>order of element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. Given an element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, its <term>order</term> is the smallest positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>r^k=1</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
    Similarly, given an integer <m>a\in \Z</m> that is relatively prime to <m>n</m>, the <term>order of <m>a</m> modulo <m>n</m></term>, denoted <m>\ord_n a</m>, is the smallest positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>a^k\equiv 1\pmod n</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
    <title>Modular exponentiation</title>
    <p>
    In what follows we will take for granted some elementary algebraic properties about exponentiation in <m>\Z/n\Z</m> that follow immediately from the corresponding properties in <m>\Z</m>. For example, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>r^{j+k} \amp = r^jr^k \amp r^{jk}=(r^j)^k=(r^k)^j</mrow>
    </md>
    for all <m>r\in \Z/n\Z</m> and nonnegative integers <m>j,k\in \Z_{\geq 0}</m>. Furthermore, if <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, then definining negative powers as <m>r^{-n}=(r^{-1})^n</m>, the above equalities hold for all integers <m>j,k\in \Z</m>. 
    </p>
    </remark>
    
    <proposition xml:id="prop_order_mod_n">
        <title>Order of modular units</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, let <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, and let <m>m=\ord r</m>. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           For all integers <m>k</m>, <m>r^k=1</m> if and only if <m>m\mid k</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>r^i=r^j</m> if and only if <m>i\equiv j\pmod m</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\{r^i\mid i\in \Z\} \amp = \{1,r,r^2,\dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and this set has cardinality <m>m</m> (<ie/>, it contains exactly <m>m</m> distinct elements). 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\ord r^i=m/\gcd(i,m)</m> for all integers <m>i\in \Z</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First assume that <m>m\mid k</m>, so that <m>k=mq</m> for some <m>q\in \Z</m>. We then have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>r^k \amp =r^{mk}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (r^m)^k</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =1^k=1</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            as desired. Conversely, 
                            assume <m>r^k=1</m> and write <m>k=qm+s</m> where <m>0\leq s &lt; m</m>, as in the division algorithm. Since 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0 \amp =r^{k}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = r^{qm+s}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = r^{qm}r^s</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =r^s \amp (m\mid qm)</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and since <m>m</m> is the smallest <em>positive</em> integer satisfying <m>r^m=1</m>, we must have <m>s=0</m>, and thus <m>m\mid k</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md number="yes">
                                <mrow>r^i=r^j \amp \iff r^{i}r^{-j}=r^{j}r^{-j}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff r^{i-j}=1</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff m\mid (i-j) \amp (\text{by } (1))</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp \iff i\equiv j\pmod m</mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>r^i=r^j</m> if and only if <m>i\equiv j\pmod m</m>, and since <m>\{0,1,\dots, m-1\}</m> form a complete set of residues modulo <m>m</m>, we have 
                            <md number="yes">
                                <mrow>\{r^i\mid i\in \Z\} \amp = \{r^0, r^1,\dots, r^{m-1}\} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =\{1,r,\dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            and these powers of <m>r</m> are all distinct. Thus the set has cardinality <m>m</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>k=m/\gcd(i,m)</m>. We will show that <m>k</m> is the smallest positive integer such that <m>(r^i)^k=1</m>, and thus that <m>\ord r^i=k</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            First observe that <m>(r^{i})^k=r^{ik}=r^{(i/\gcd(i,m))m}=1</m>, since <m>m\mid (i/\gcd(i,m))m</m>. Now assume that <m>\ell</m> is a positive integer satisfying <m>(r^i)^\ell=r^{i\ell}=1</m>. It follows that <m>m\mid i\ell</m>. But then 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m/\gcd(i,m) \amp \mid (i/\gcd(i,m))\ell</mrow>
                            </md>.
                            Since <m>m/\gcd(i,m)</m> and <m>i/\gcd(i,m)</m> are relatively prime, it follows that <m>k=m/\gcd(i,m)\mid \ell</m>, and hence that <m>k\leq \ell</m>, since <m>k</m> and <m>\ell</m> are positive. This proves <m>k</m> is the smallest positive integer such that <m>(r^i)^k=1</m>, and thus that <m>\ord r^i=k</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <definition xml:id="d_cyclic_group">
    <title>Primitive root</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m>. The <term>cyclic group generated by <m>r</m></term>, denoted <m>\langle r\rangle</m>, is the set of all integer powers of <m>r</m>: <ie/>, 
    <md>
        <mrow>\angvec{r} \amp = \{r^i\mid i\in \Z\}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \{1,r, \dots, r^{m-1}\}</mrow>
    </md>,
    where <m>m=\ord r</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        A <term>primitive root</term> (or <term>cyclic generator</term>) of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is an element <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> satisfying <m>\angvec{r}=(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_primitive_roots">
    <title>Primitive roots</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Compute the order of all elements of <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> for the given modulus <m>n</m>, and decide whether <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> has a primitive root. 
    </p>
    <p>
    Additionally, if a primitive root <m>r\in (\Z/n\Z)^*</m> does exist, verify the order formula for each power <m>r^i</m> given in <xref ref="prop_order_mod_n"/>.
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=7</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=12</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>n=25</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    For each modulus below, we will drop most of our notational baggage and simply write <m>a</m> instead of <m>[a]_n</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                We have <m>(\Z/7\Z)^*=\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}</m>. Computing successive powers of these elements leads to the following order computations:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\ord 1 \amp =1 \amp \ord 2=3\amp \ord 3\amp =6</mrow>
                    <mrow>\ord 4 \amp = 3 \amp \ord 5\amp =6 \amp \ord 6\amp =2</mrow>
                </md>.
                Since <m>\ord 3=\ord 5=6</m>, we see that both of these elements are primitive roots in <m>\Z/7\Z</m>. Let's verify that <m>\angvec{3}=\angvec{5}=(\Z/7\Z)^*</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>\angvec{3} \amp =\{1, 3, 3^2, 3^3, 3^4, 3^5, 3^6\}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \{1,3,2,6, 4,5\}=(\Z/7\Z)^*</mrow>
                    <mrow>\angvec{5} \amp = \{1, 5, 5^2, 5^3, 5^4, 5^5, 5^6\} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \{1,5,4,6,2,3\}=(\Z/7\Z)^*</mrow>
                </md>.
                Lastly, let's verify the order formula for the powers of <m>3</m>. 
            </p>
            <table>
                <title>Orders of powers of <m>3</m></title>
                <tabular>
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                        <cell><m>i</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3^i</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\ord 3^i</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/\gcd(i,6)</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/6=1\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/1=6\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/2=3\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/3=2\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/2=3\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6/2=3\, \checkmark</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                We have <m>(\Z/12\Z)^*=\{1,5,7,11\}</m> and we easily compute
                <md>
                    <mrow>\ord 1 \amp = 1 \amp \ord 5\amp=2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\ord 7 \amp =2 \amp \ord 11\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>.
                Since no element has order 4, there is no primitive root for <m>(\Z/12\Z)^*</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Since <m>\gcd(a,25)=1</m> if and only if <m>5\nmid a</m>, the units of <m>\Z/25\Z</m> are the elements of the form <m>[a]_{25}</m>, where <m>5\nmid a</m>. There are <m>20=25-5</m> of these. Let's use Sage to see whether any of these have order 20.  
            </p>
            <sage>
                <input>
                    R=Integers(25)
                    for a in R:
                        if a.is_unit(): print((a,a.multiplicative_order()))
                </input>
                <output>
                    (1, 1)
(2, 20)
(3, 20)
(4, 10)
(6, 5)
(7, 4)
(8, 20)
(9, 10)
(11, 5)
(12, 20)
(13, 20)
(14, 10)
(16, 5)
(17, 20)
(18, 4)
(19, 10)
(21, 5)
(22, 20)
(23, 20)
(24, 2)
                </output>
            </sage>
            <p>
                We see that <m>2</m> has order <m>20=\abs{(Z\25\Z)^*)}</m>, and thus that <m>2</m> is a primitive root. We leave it to the reader to verify the order formula for powers of <m>2</m> as we did in the first part.
            </p>
            <p>
                On a separate note, notice that there are 8 distinct primitive roots here: <m>2,3,8,12,13,17,22,23</m>. In the next sections we will derive a formula for the number of distinct primitive roots modulo, if one does indeed exist. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
        Our example makes one thing clear: some moduli admit primitive roots; others do not. In the next section we will see that when <m>n=p</m> is prime, then a primitive root is guaranteed to exist. 
    </p>
</subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_sage_order">
    <title>Sage examples</title>
<p>
    Here are some Sage cells to play with. 
</p>
<sage>
    <input>
        
    </input>
    <output>
        
    </output>
</sage>
<sage>
    <input>
        
    </input>
    <output>
        
    </output>
</sage>
<project xml:id="sage_order_primitive">
    <title>Order and primitive elements</title>
    <p>
        For an element <c>a</c> of <c>Integers(n)</c>, the method <c>a.is_primitive_root()</c> determines whether <c>a</c> is a primitive root.
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            R=Integers(25)
            for a in R: print((a,a.is_primitive_root()))
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        For an <em>invertible</em> element <c>a</c> of <c>Integers(n)</c>, the method <c>a.multiplicative_order()</c> computes the order of <c>a</c>. If <c>a</c> is not invertible, then <c>a.multiplicative_order()</c> raises an error. We can test for invertibility using the <c>a.is_unit()</c> method. 
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            R=Integers(25)
            for a in R: 
                if a.is_unit(): print((a,a.multiplicative_order()))
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
    <p>
        Lastly, a modular ring object <c>R=Integers(n)</c> has a method <c>R.unit_group()</c> that returns <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m>, which itself has lots of useful methods that you can explore using <c>dir(G)</c>. The method <c>G.is_cyclic()</c> determines whether <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> has a primitive element. (Terminology-wise, <m>(\Z/n\Z)^*</m> is a mathematical object called a <em>group</em>; and a group is <em>cyclic</em> precisely when it can be expressed as <m>\angvec{r}</m> for some element <m>r</m>, just as in <xref ref="d_cyclic_group"/>.)
    </p>
    <p>
        Let's investigate which moduli <m>n</m> admit a primitive root. 
    </p>
    <sage>
        <input>
            for n in range(2,51):
                R=Integers(n)
                G=R.unit_group()
                print("Primitive root exists for Z/%sZ? %s" % (n,G.is_cyclic()))
        </input>
        <output>
            
        </output>
    </sage>
</project>
    </subsection>
</section>